{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473976"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:16:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:16:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11606"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11606"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.1,0.78,0.08,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4233"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46178"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4233"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11606"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31103"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"148"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5574"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46283"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46178"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with a seven-day history of sore throat and fever. Her mother describes a rash that started on the child\u0027s trunk and gradually spread to her arms and legs. She has no significant medical history and is up to date with immunisations. On examination, she appears unwell with a temperature of 38.0\u00b0C, pulse rate 120/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, and SpO2 98% on room air. The oral mucosae appear erythematous with a strawberry tongue. There is a maculopapular rash over her trunk and an erythematous desquamating rash involving the palms and soles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bone marrow biopsy","Erythrocyte sedimentation rate","Echocardiography","Full blood count","C-reactive protein"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EKawasaki disease (KD) should be considered in any child with a febrile exanthematous illness and evidence of inflammation, particularly if it persists longer than four days. The following criteria can be used to make a diagnosis of KD:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFever persisting for 5 days, PLUS 4 of the 5 following criteria:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EConjunctival injection\u003C/em\u003E\u003Cbr\u003EBilateral, bulbar, conjunctival injection without exudate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003ELymphadenopathy\u003C/em\u003E \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECervical, often \u0026gt;1.5 cm usually unilateral \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003ERash\u003C/em\u003E \u003Cbr\u003EMaculopapular, diffuse erythroderma or erythema multiforme \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EChanges of lips or oral mucosa\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERed cracked lips, \u003Cstrong\u003Estrawberry tongue\u003C/strong\u003E or diffuse erythema of oropharynx \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EChanges to extremities\u003C/em\u003E \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythema and oedema of palms and soles in acute phase and periungal desquamation in subacute phase \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, it is important to recognise that there are cases of \u0022incomplete Kawasaki disease\u0022. Such cases present with prolonged fever or fleeting clinical signs, but they may be at risk of developing coronary artery aneurysms (CAA). It is important to keep a high index of suspicion in such cases and perform \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiography\u003C/strong\u003E. Echocardiography may reveal coronary vasculitis, thereby confirming the diagnosis of KD. In any patient who does not fulfil the diagnostic criteria of KD, echocardiographic findings can confirm the diagnosis. All patients will need echocardiographic evaluation whether they have a complete or incomplete diagnosis. This is to evaluate for presence of CAA or other cardiac manifestations of KD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of complete Kawasaki disease (five criteria) is essentially a clinical one and whilst some laboratory investigations may be supportive, the only investigation required is an echocardiogram. In cases of incomplete Kawasaki disease, where the patient presents with fever for five days or longer, 2 or 3 of the principal clinical features, then laboratory findings may help in confirming the disease, but looking for echocardiographic abnormalities would be the most appropriate investigation. Suggestive laboratory findings include elevated erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR), elevated C-reactive protein (CRP), hypoalbuminaemia, anaemia, elevated alanine aminotransferase (ALT), thrombocytosis, leukocytosis, and pyuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone marrow biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in the diagnosis of KD. However it may be considered if a child is suspected of developing macrophage activation syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn elevated \u003Cstrong\u003Eerythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR), C-reactive protein (CRP)\u003C/strong\u003E or white cell count (\u003Cstrong\u003Efull blood count\u003C/strong\u003E) can support a diagnosis of KD in a suspected case but they are non-specific markers of systemic inflammation. The most important investigation in the current scenario is an echocardiogram.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Early echocardiography is recommended when a patient is suspected to have Kawasaki disease but does not fulfill the diagnostic criteria."],"references":["de Graeff N, Groot N, Ozen S, Eleftheriou D, Avcin T, Bader-Meunier B, Dolezalova P, Feldman BM, Kone-Paut I, Lahdenne P, McCann L. European consensus-based recommendations for the diagnosis and treatment of Kawasaki disease\u2013the SHARE initiative. Rheumatology. 2019 Apr 1;58(4):672-82"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31103"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11606"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31103"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-30T19:30:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-03T10:26:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4233"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46178"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1